The paper deals with the complexity of dynamic programming, which is a fundamental topic in computer science and falls under the category of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the fine-grained complexity of the problem, which involves analyzing the running time of algorithms in terms of lower bounds on basic operations such as comparisons and additions. This suggests that the paper could also be classified under computational complexity (cs.CC) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The paper also involves geometric concepts such as nested boxes and vector domination, which are common in computational geometry (cs.CG). Finally, the paper discusses the use of parallelism in solving the problem, which is a topic in machine learning and artificial intelligence (cs.LG).
